## Formalization Rules

Apply these rules to the **entire** rewritten theory, not just the mismatched sentences.

RULE 1  ‚Äî Every domain entity MUST be a named `Const`. Never rely on unnamed sort elements;
          Z3 would assign internal names like `Sort!val!0` that downstream code cannot reference.

RULE 2  ‚Äî `ForAll`/`Exists` quantifier list must be non-empty. `ForAll([], expr)` is a runtime error.

RULE 3  ‚Äî Bound variable must be a separate `Const` from all entity constants. Declare
          `x = Const('x', Sort)` and use it exclusively inside `ForAll`/`Exists`; never reuse
          an entity constant as the bound variable.

RULE 4  ‚Äî Universal claims ‚Üí `ForAll`; existential ‚Üí `Exists`; "No X is Y" ‚Üí
          `ForAll([v], Not(And(is_X(v), is_Y(v))))`. Conditional "if‚Ä¶then" ‚Üí `Implies`.
          Bare generic plurals: a bare plural subject without a determiner ("Vacuums suck",
          "Dogs bark") expresses a universal claim ‚Äî NOT a fact about a singleton entity.
          ‚Üí `ForAll([v], Implies(is_vacuum(v), sucks(v)))`   ‚úì
          ‚Üí `sucks(Vacuums)`   ‚Üê singleton entity mistake   ‚úó

RULE 5  ‚Äî No solver calls, no print statements, no assertions. Only declarations and assignments.
          Do NOT write `Solver()`, `s.check()`, `print(...)`, or `assert`.

RULE 6  ‚Äî Only `DeclareSort` is allowed. Never use `IntSort()`, `StringSort()`, `RealSort()`,
          or `SeqSort()`. Years, counts, and string-valued facts must be modelled as named `Const`
          of a declared sort.

RULE 7  ‚Äî One NL property = one predicate. Each independently assertable property must be its own
          predicate. Never compress "private Ivy League research university" into one opaque name ‚Äî
          declare `is_private`, `is_ivy_league`, `is_research` separately.

RULE 8  ‚Äî Every identifier used in `premises` or `q` must exactly match a previously declared name.
          Verify every identifier before finishing.

RULE 9  ‚Äî `premises` must align one-to-one with the numbered NL premises: N premises in ‚Üí exactly
          N top-level formulas in `premises[]`, in the same order. Do not omit, merge, or split.

RULE 10 ‚Äî Uninterpreted comparison predicates (`more_than`, `equal_to`, `no_more_than`, etc.)
          require mathematical axioms (asymmetry, transitivity) added as `background_constraints`.
          Omit `background_constraints` entirely if no comparison predicates are used.

RULE 11 ‚Äî Synonymous NL phrases must map to the SAME predicate name throughout. Different surface
          forms describing the same action or relation share one predicate. Splitting synonyms
          silently breaks inference chains.

RULE 12 ‚Äî "X is a [noun/type]" means a TYPE predicate, never entity equality. Translate "X is a
          conductor" as `is_conductor(X)`, never as `X == conductor_entity`. Entity equality (`==`)
          is only correct for explicit identity statements like "X and Y are the same individual."

RULE 13 ‚Äî De Morgan negation scope: "neither A nor B" / "not A or B" with a SINGLE scoped
          negation over a disjunction means And(Not(A), Not(B)), NOT Or(Not(A), Not(B)).

          - "X is neither a cat nor a dog"  ‚Üí And(Not(is_cat(X)), Not(is_dog(X)))   ‚Üê De Morgan
          - "X is not a cat, or not a dog"  ‚Üí Or(Not(is_cat(X)), Not(is_dog(X)))    ‚Üê two separate negations

          Test: is there ONE "not" scoping over "A or B"?
            Yes ‚Üí And(Not(A), Not(B)).
            No, each clause carries its own negation ‚Üí Or(Not(A), Not(B)).

